Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

The mean cost of the order is 16.50 dollars, which means that on average, the customers spend 16.50 dollars per order.

The median cost of the order is 14.14 dollars, which is the value that separates the lower 50% of the data from the upper 50% of the data. Since the median is less than the mean, this suggests that the distribution of the 'cost_of_order' column is a bit right-skewed, with some higher cost orders that pull the mean up.

The standard deviation of the 'cost_of_order' column is 7.48 dollars, which means that the data is spread out around the mean by an average of 7.48 dollars. This gives an indication of the amount of variability in the data.

Multivariate Analysis¶

Question 12: Perform a multivariate analysis to explore relationships between the important variables in the dataset. (It is a good idea to explore relations between numerical variables as well as relations between numerical and categorical variables) [10 marks]¶

Correlation among variables

In [329]:
# select the numerical variables
numerical_vars = ['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time']

# calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = df[numerical_vars].corr()

# visualize the correlation matrix using a heatmap
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.show()
  • The correlation coefficient between 'cost_of_the_order' and 'food_preparation_time' is 0.042. Since the value is close to 0, we can conclude that there is a weak positive correlation between these two variables. This means that as the cost of the order increases, the food preparation time tends to increase slightly as well, but the relationship is not very strong.
  • The correlation coefficient between 'cost_of_the_order' and 'delivery_time' is -0.03. Since the value is close to 0, we can conclude that there is a weak negative correlation between these two variables. This means that as the cost of the order increases, the delivery time tends to decrease slightly, but again, the relationship is not very strong.
  • The correlation coefficient between 'food_preparation_time' and 'delivery_time' is 0.011. Since the value is very close to 0, we can conclude that there is no significant correlation between these two variables. This means that the food preparation time and the delivery time do not tend to be related to each other.
  • Overall, the heatmap suggests that there is no strong correlation between the numerical variables in the dataset, and that they may be relatively independent of each other. However, it's important to note that correlation does not imply causation, so we cannot make any causal inferences from these results alone.

Cost of order VS Cuisine Type

In [333]:

sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(12,8)})

The minimum cost of an order across all cuisine types falls within the range of 4-7 dollars, except for French and Spanish cuisine, where the minimum order cost is higher than 10 dollars.

For most cuisine types, the 25th percentile of the order cost is around 13 dollars, indicating that 25% of the orders cost less than this amount. Additionally, 50% of the cuisine types have a median order cost of less than 15 dollars. The only exception is French cuisine, which has a median cost of over 20 dollars. With the exception of Middle Eastern and French cuisine, all other types of cuisine have a 75th percentile order cost lower than 25 dollars.

While French cuisine may be slightly more expensive than other cuisines at the minimum order cost level, when we examine its 25th percentile, median, and 75th percentile, it falls within the same range as other cuisines. Additionally, the maximum cost of French cuisine is not the most expensive among all cuisines if we exclude outliers. In fact, Chinese cuisine has the highest maximum cost among all cuisines, excluding outliers.

In [334]:
# Define a function to find the outliers
def find_outliers(data, column, multiplier=1.5):
    Q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - (multiplier * IQR)
    upper_bound = Q3 + (multiplier * IQR)
    
    return data[(data[column] < lower_bound) | (data[column] > upper_bound)]

# Filter the data for each cuisine type
korean_df = df[df['cuisine_type'] == 'Korean']
mediterranean_df = df[df['cuisine_type'] == 'Mediterranean']
vietnamese_df = df[df['cuisine_type'] == 'Vietnamese']

# Find and print the outlier values for each cuisine type
korean_outliers = find_outliers(korean_df, 'cost_of_the_order')
mediterranean_outliers = find_outliers(mediterranean_df, 'cost_of_the_order')
vietnamese_outliers = find_outliers(vietnamese_df, 'cost_of_the_order')

print("Korean Cuisine Outliers:\n", korean_outliers)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [344]:
# Calculate commission earned for each order
df['commission'] = 0
df.loc[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, 'commission'] = df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25
df.loc[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20), 'commission'] = df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15

# Calculate net revenue
net_revenue = df['commission'].sum()

print('Net revenue generated by the company: $', round(net_revenue, 2))

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The dataset contains information on 1898 orders that were made by 1200 different customers, across 178 different restaurants.
  • Weekends are the most popular time for orders, with more than twice as many orders as weekdays.
  • American cuisine is the most popular, followed by Japanese cuisine.
  • Approximately 89% of orders are completed, including food preparation and delivery, within 60 minutes.
  • About 29.2% of orders cost over $20, indicating that the price of food is reasonable.
  • The delivery time on weekends and weekdays differs only by five minutes, indicating that there are enough human resources to handle the increased orders and busy environment during weekends.
  • It appears that there is no strong relationship between customers' ratings and food preparation time, delivery time, or cost of orders.

Recommendations:¶

  • A recommendation for obtaining a more comprehensive understanding of customer satisfaction would be to gather data on orders for all days of the week, including holidays, and during lunch, tea, and dinner hours to analyze order volume. Additionally, collecting more information such as restaurant location and the numbers of delivery person/driver would provide more insights into the data and help to better understand the relationship between factors such as delivery time, food preparation time, and customers' ratings.

  • Without additional information or context, it is difficult to definitively determine the exact meaning of each rating. However, generally speaking, a rating of 3 out of 5 is typically considered average or satisfactory, while a rating of 4 or 5 out of 5 is generally considered good or very good. It is unlikely that a rating of 5 out of 5 would represent a level of extreme dissatisfaction. Additionally, since we do not have any values for 0-2 stars in the dataset, we cannot determine whether the 3-star ratings correspond to 'poor' or 'moderate' or any other description. It is always best to consult with the department that collected the data to obtain a more accurate and detailed understanding of the rating system used.

  • In order to improve our rating system and reduce the number of "Not given" ratings, we can explore ways to gather more feedback from customers. To achieve this, we can switch to a 5-star rating system, where 1 star represents unsatisfactory and 5 stars represent very satisfactory. Additionally, we can add a comment section to the questionnaire to encourage customers to leave more detailed feedback. As an incentive for customers to provide feedback, we can offer random discounts for their next purchase. Also, we need a more detailed rating system data, to obtain the feedback from food quality to cost of the food, so that we can gain a better understanding of the data.

  • As American cuisine is the most popular cuisine among our customers, we can consider inviting more American restaurants to join our business. To further promote American cuisine and attract food enthusiasts, we can also organize American food festivals.
